</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="178.[151,1437,151,1112]" box="[199,922,223,248]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis box="[199,273,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Larva.</emphasis>
Described for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1901" box="[440,566,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="procerus">
<emphasis box="[440,566,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">P. procerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler, G. C. &amp; Wheeler, J." box="[608,918,223,248]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="443 - 462" refId="ref167049" refString="Wheeler, G. C. &amp; Wheeler, J. (1964) The ant larvae of the subfamily Ponerinae: supplement. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 57, 443 - 462." type="journal article" year="1964">Wheeler &amp; Wheeler (1964)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="178.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,260,285]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Geographic distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[511,685,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[511,685,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to central and western Africa, ranging from 
<collectingCountry name="Sierra Leone" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Sierra Leone</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[264,337,296,320]" name="Kenya" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and as far south as 
<collectingCountry box="[581,656,295,320]" name="Gabon" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Gabon</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[762,1125,295,320]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Democratic Republic of Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B." box="[1143,1312,295,320]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref133281" refString="Bolton, B. (1975 b) A revision of the African ponerine ant genus Psalidomyrmex Andre (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 32, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="1975">Bolton, 1975b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B. &amp; Brown, W. L. Jr." pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref133506" refString="Bolton, B. &amp; Brown, W. L. Jr. (2002) Loboponera gen. n. and a review of the Afrotropical Plectroctena genus group (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 71, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0968045402000019" type="journal article" year="2002">Bolton &amp; Brown, 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="178" pageNumber="179" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="178.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,367,392]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Ecology and behavior.</emphasis>
Very little is known about the ecology and behavior of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[1105,1279,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1105,1279,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They nest in rotting logs, in the soil beneath rotting logs (
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B." box="[652,818,404,429]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref133281" refString="Bolton, B. (1975 b) A revision of the African ponerine ant genus Psalidomyrmex Andre (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 32, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="1975">
<collectingRegion box="[652,733,404,429]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Bolton</collectingRegion>
, 1975b
</bibRefCitation>
), or in deserted termitaries (Déjean 
<emphasis box="[1222,1279,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">et al.</emphasis>
, 1996, 1997), and workers forage individually in rotting wood or in leaf litter (
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B." box="[908,1077,439,464]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref133281" refString="Bolton, B. (1975 b) A revision of the African ponerine ant genus Psalidomyrmex Andre (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 32, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="1975">
<collectingRegion box="[908,988,439,464]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Bolton</collectingRegion>
, 1975b
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1901" box="[1100,1229,441,464]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="procerus">
<emphasis box="[1100,1229,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">P. procerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to be a specialist predator of earthworms (
<bibRefCitation author="Levieux, J." box="[543,711,476,501]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="48 - 53" refId="ref151020" refString="Levieux, J. (1982) A comparison of the ground dwelling ant populations between a Guinea savanna and an evergreen rain forest of the Ivory Coast. Biology of Social Insects. Proceedings of the Ninth Congress of the IUSSI, pp. 48 - 53." type="proceedings paper" year="1982">Lévieux, 1982</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dejean, A. &amp; Olmsted, I. &amp; Camal, J. F." box="[723,942,476,501]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="57 - 76" refId="ref138105" refString="Dejean, A., Olmsted, I. &amp; Camal, J. F. (1992) Interaction between Atta cephalotes and arboreal ants in the Biosphere reserve Sian Ka'an (Quintana Roo, Mexico): efficient protection of the trees (Hymenoptera, Formicidae). Sociobiology, 20 (1), 57 - 76." type="journal article" year="1992">
Déjean 
<emphasis box="[810,867,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">et al.</emphasis>
, 1992
</bibRefCitation>
), and though the feeding habits of the other species is unknown, it seems likely that they too may feed on earthworms, given the apparently specialized mandibular structure of the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="178.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,737,583,608]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Phylogenetic and taxonomic considerations.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[748,922,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[748,922,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Andre, E." box="[1122,1279,583,608]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="311 - 327" refId="ref131370" refString="Andre, E. (1890) Materiaux pour servir a la faune myrmecologique de Sierra-Leone (Afrique occidentale). Revue d'Entomologie (Caen), 9, 311 - 327." type="journal article" year="1890">
<collectingRegion box="[1122,1192,583,608]" country="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" name="Saint Andrew" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">André</collectingRegion>
(1890)
</bibRefCitation>
to house the single species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[322,469,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveolatus">
<emphasis box="[322,469,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">P. foveolatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B." box="[487,664,620,645]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref133281" refString="Bolton, B. (1975 b) A revision of the African ponerine ant genus Psalidomyrmex Andre (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 32, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="1975">
<collectingRegion box="[487,563,620,645]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Bolton</collectingRegion>
(1975b)
</bibRefCitation>
revised the genus, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B. &amp; Brown, W. L. Jr." box="[950,1234,620,645]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref133506" refString="Bolton, B. &amp; Brown, W. L. Jr. (2002) Loboponera gen. n. and a review of the Afrotropical Plectroctena genus group (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 71, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0968045402000019" type="journal article" year="2002">
<collectingRegion box="[950,1026,620,645]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Bolton</collectingRegion>
&amp; Brown (2002)
</bibRefCitation>
gave an updated diagnosis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="178.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">
<bibRefCitation author="Andre, E." box="[199,354,692,717]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="311 - 327" refId="ref131370" refString="Andre, E. (1890) Materiaux pour servir a la faune myrmecologique de Sierra-Leone (Afrique occidentale). Revue d'Entomologie (Caen), 9, 311 - 327." type="journal article" year="1890">
<collectingRegion box="[199,269,692,717]" country="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" name="Saint Andrew" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">André</collectingRegion>
(1890)
</bibRefCitation>
apparently believed that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[650,824,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[650,824,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[1096,1231,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Belonopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1096,1231,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Belonopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to supposed similarities in their mandibular structure. However, P.S. Ward (pers. comm.) found that 
<taxonomicName box="[1135,1270,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Belonopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1135,1270,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Belonopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="sensu Brown" baseAuthorityYear="1973" box="[151,310,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,310,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Pachycondyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group while 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, C." box="[478,660,764,789]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="201 - 250" refId="ref161753" refString="Schmidt, C. (2013) Molecular phylogenetics of ponerine ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Ponerinae). Zootaxa, 3647 (2), 201 - 250. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3647.2.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Schmidt (2013)</bibRefCitation>
placed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[760,934,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[760,934,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName box="[1031,1173,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plectroctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1031,1173,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Plectroctena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. The only real similarity in the mandibles of these genera is the attenuated apical tooth, which occurs in at least two other ponerine genera (
<taxonomicName box="[347,489,837,860]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Emeryopone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,489,837,860]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Emeryopone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[542,744,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Thaumatomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[542,744,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Thaumatomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and this similarity is clearly convergent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="178.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[199,373,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,373,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been grouped with 
<taxonomicName box="[692,834,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plectroctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[692,834,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Plectroctena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since 
<bibRefCitation author="Emery, C." box="[926,1092,871,896]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 125" refId="ref141346" refString="Emery, C. (1911) Hymenoptera. Fam. Formicidae. Subfam. Ponerinae. Genera Insectorum, 118, 1 - 125." type="journal article" year="1911">Emery (1911)</bibRefCitation>
included it in his subtribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1911" box="[151,310,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Plectroctenini">Plectroctenini</taxonomicName>
, though this was based on weak evidence. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B." box="[812,973,908,933]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="309 - 338" refId="ref133186" refString="Bolton, B. (1974) A revision of the ponerine ant genus Plectroctena F. Smith (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 30, 309 - 338." type="journal article" year="1974">
<collectingRegion box="[812,888,908,933]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Bolton</collectingRegion>
(1974)
</bibRefCitation>
argued for a close relationship between these genera based on the structure of the mesosoma, petiole and gaster, a similar reduction in palpal segments, and male morphological characteristics. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B. &amp; Brown, W. L. Jr." box="[568,849,980,1005]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref133506" refString="Bolton, B. &amp; Brown, W. L. Jr. (2002) Loboponera gen. n. and a review of the Afrotropical Plectroctena genus group (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology), 71, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0968045402000019" type="journal article" year="2002">
<collectingRegion box="[568,644,980,1005]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Bolton</collectingRegion>
&amp; Brown (2002)
</bibRefCitation>
found additional evidence for a close relationship between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[255,429,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[255,429,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[491,633,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plectroctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,633,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Plectroctena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the structure of the anterior petiolar articulatory surface (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Fisher, B. L." box="[151,300,1052,1077]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="111 - 118" refId="ref142162" refString="Fisher, B. L. (2006) Boloponera vicans gen. n. and sp. n. and two new species of the Plectroctena genus group (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Myrmecologische Nachrichten, 8, 111 - 118." type="journal article" year="2006">Fisher, 2006</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, C." box="[325,521,1052,1077]" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" pagination="201 - 250" refId="ref161753" refString="Schmidt, C. (2013) Molecular phylogenetics of ponerine ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Ponerinae). Zootaxa, 3647 (2), 201 - 250. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3647.2.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Schmidt's (2013)</bibRefCitation>
molecular phylogeny of the 
<taxonomicName box="[873,985,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
confirms this close relationship, with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1890" box="[151,325,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Psalidomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,325,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Psalidomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resolved as sister to 
<taxonomicName box="[559,696,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Loboponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[559,696,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Loboponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName box="[726,868,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plectroctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[726,868,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Plectroctena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Fisher" authorityYear="2006" box="[882,1014,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Boloponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="178" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[882,1014,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="178" pageNumber="179">Boloponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also probably in this sister clade.
</paragraph>
